docs.abstract: The tech mogul, whose Craigslist site helped replace newspaper classifieds, has given $50 million to revitalize local reporting in New York — including a new gift on Wednesday.
docs.snippet: The tech mogul, whose Craigslist site helped replace newspaper classifieds, has given $50 million to revitalize local reporting in New York — including a new gift on Wednesday.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — Craig Newmark, so often accused of destroying journalism, is now doing his best to revive it.

headline.main: Craig Newmark, Newspaper Villain, Is Working to Save Journalism
headline.print_headline: How a Villain to Newspapers Is Trying to Save Journalism

docs.abstract: Though sales of its devices have been slow, the search giant unveiled the Pixel 3, a smart speaker with a built-in screen and a tablet that doubles as a PC.
docs.snippet: Though sales of its devices have been slow, the search giant unveiled the Pixel 3, a smart speaker with a built-in screen and a tablet that doubles as a PC.
docs.lead_paragraph: MOUNTAIN VIEW, Calif. — For much of the last decade, Apple and Samsung have dominated sales of smartphones. So why would anyone bother trying to sell a new phone?

headline.main: New Pixel Phones and Other Gadgets Keep Google in the Hardware Hunt
headline.print_headline: New Devices Keep Google in Gadget Hunt

docs.abstract: Twice a year, Sony/ATV Music invites 15 to 20 of its clients to multiday “sync camps,” where they try to create songs for commercials, movie trailers and video games.
docs.snippet: Twice a year, Sony/ATV Music invites 15 to 20 of its clients to multiday “sync camps,” where they try to create songs for commercials, movie trailers and video games.
docs.lead_paragraph: When Bose was trying to find the right song for a commercial promoting its latest wireless headphones in partnership with the National Football League last fall, it didn’t dig through catalogs of blockbuster hits from big-name rock stars or hip-hop artists. Instead, it chose a newly written song — “Get Loud for Me” — by a little-known singer named Gizzle.

headline.main: Need a Song for Your Commercial? Try These Campers
headline.print_headline: Need a Song for Your Commercial? Instead of a Star, Try These Campers

docs.abstract: Beijing is putting billions of dollars behind facial recognition and other technologies to track and control its citizens.
docs.snippet: Beijing is putting billions of dollars behind facial recognition and other technologies to track and control its citizens.
docs.lead_paragraph: ZHENGZHOU, China — In the Chinese city of Zhengzhou, a police officer wearing facial recognition glasses spotted a heroin smuggler at a train station.

headline.main: Inside China’s Dystopian Dreams: A.I., Shame and Lots of Cameras
headline.print_headline: With Cameras And A.I., China Closes Its Grip

docs.abstract: Some in China are building a future that isn’t quite ready. Still, the exuberance may be a good thing, as useful products find their place and bad ones disappear.
docs.snippet: Some in China are building a future that isn’t quite ready. Still, the exuberance may be a good thing, as useful products find their place and bad ones disappear.
docs.lead_paragraph: SHANGHAI — The mind-reading headsets won’t read minds. The fire-detecting machine has been declared a safety hazard. The robot waiter can’t be trusted with the soup.

headline.main: Wild About Tech, China Even Loves Robot Waiters That Can’t Serve
headline.print_headline: Wild About Tech, China Even Loves Waiters Too Clunky to Serve

docs.abstract: Bureaucratic reshuffling made it difficult for the company, an emblem of Chinese innovation, to get approvals to make money off new games, hurting earnings.
docs.snippet: Bureaucratic reshuffling made it difficult for the company, an emblem of Chinese innovation, to get approvals to make money off new games, hurting earnings.
docs.lead_paragraph: SHANGHAI — Its chat app has inspired Silicon Valley. It owns some of the biggest video game franchises in the world. And after years of growth it has become one of the largest internet companies in the world.

headline.main: Tencent, the Chinese Internet Giant, Stumbles. Beijing Gets the Blame
headline.print_headline: Tech Giant Tencent Stumbles, And Cursors Point at Beijing

docs.abstract: Facebook gained approval to open a Chinese subsidiary on July 18, according to a Chinese government filing. The social network has been blocked in China for years.
docs.snippet: Facebook gained approval to open a Chinese subsidiary on July 18, according to a Chinese government filing. The social network has been blocked in China for years.
docs.lead_paragraph: SHANGHAI — After a decade of effort in which Facebook’s progress at courting China often seemed to stall, the social network finally gained an official status in the country — at least temporarily.

headline.main: Facebook Gains Status in China, at Least for a Moment
headline.print_headline: Facebook Gets China’s Nod For Subsidiary, Apparently

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Federal Reserve officials presented a rosy economic report card to Congress on Friday, playing down risks to growth from trade tensions and declaring that the financial system is “substantially more resilient than during the decade before the financial crisis.”
